<Time>1616081558707</Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
We drove Saline Valley Road to Hunter Canyon Road to get to the Playa. If it‚Äôs rained recently, don‚Äôt go that way unless you have a decent AWD/4WD vehicle with more than 8‚Äù clearance. The Playa was beautiful. Sadly, the only tracks we saw were made by cars, not  rocks. Bad timing on my partüò´

The valley is stunning, and if you are lucky, you‚Äôll get to see more stars in the night sky than you‚Äôve ever witnessed before as you drive that long, 21 mile dirt road, back to the main paved highway.

I blew a tyre... I recommend slow and steady driving, don‚Äôt get cockyüòú< /text>

<Rate>5<//Rate><text>I was here on October/11/20.
There are few different paths to get in to the trail head, we got in by the super, super,super terrible path, and got out by a little easier path.
This place has a lot to exploring, learning, and memorizing.
We were walking around 2.5 miles with negative elevation gain.
Playa is one of the most flattest nature surface on earth.
Those rocks sailing across the fine clay surface have created their own trails.
Rocks have all different sizes and shapes,some heavier than another, each making its own unique trail, leading off in different directions.
I was walking along to those tracks, it‚Äôs moved quite long way, I couldn‚Äôt find their destination, some of the trails looked like parallel lines, another looked like circled.
I couldn‚Äôt believe it, Mother‚Äôs Nature gives us so much to learn.
This is place for
YOU TO CHECK IT OUT!!!</text><Gmap_id>0x80bf60974992ace9:0xfd5de26ead99a77a<//Gmap_id><userid>106702810914006292937<//userid>< time>

< Text>
Absolutely spectacular!!! The Racetrack itself, a dry clay lake bed, perfectly smooth and so beautiful with a rock formation in the middle called ‚ÄúThe Grandstand‚Äù because it reminds of a place for spectators to watch the race. What paradise! Perfectly quiet and inspiring. Do not miss the Playa where the rocks move by themselves. It is about a half mile walk from the car. The ride there is rough but so worth it.<//Text>

<rating>4</rating><review>We went there with our compact suv GMC Terrain with not suitable for this road tires. And it was a bit scary to drive this long 22 mile distance off road. Max 30 mph in flat roads took us approximately 2,5 hr each way. And we saw a guy with 4x4 broken the whole wheel that tow-away only could get it out. Also we saw some sedan cars, but I wouldn't recommend in some areas of the road. Also when you reach the pool go to the last parking lot to the very end of the playa. There are all the sliding rocks. In first parkings you will have to search for them a looong way and be dissapointed not to see them. Also be sure to download offline maps.me to get the way back in the whole death valley as there is no internet connection and be sure to get the full fuel tank before entering death valley. No gas stations around. Also the whole risk of getting there and seeing not so much sliding rocks disappointed me that I wouldn't reccomend to go there at all.<//review>< pics>

<Rating>5<//Rating><userid>103070816155020614859<//userid><Text>Magical place! You have to travel an Extremely brutal rock and gravel road for an hour and a half to get here. Nothing too technical just a rough washboard surface that is relentless. You actually appreciate when you get to some slow technical sections just to break up the constant pounding. The playa itself is amazing! A totally flat surface for miles. It is hard to find the traces of moving rocks. Most are found in the Southern section far from the Grandstand. None<//resp>
< text>
The Racetrack Playa is quite an amazing place to visit. If you're lucky, you'll see the rocks that "move on their own", leaving a trail behind them in the dry bed that makes up most of the area. In the middle of the dry bed, you can walk to some rock formations and climb the rocks (not very high). You can just sit there and  absorb the fastness of the dessert dry bed surrounded by the  mountains.  Nearby is a mountain that you can consider scaling if you have sufficient time. But plan your trip carefully so you do not get caught by the sudden darkness when the sun sets behind the mountains. Make sure you have sufficient light, water and food! It gets real cold in winter after the sun sets!< /text>

<user_name>David Nasr< /user_name>< user>

< Review>
We made the drive on a Toyota Camry , took us two hours one way, had to be extra careful due to the low clearance of the vehicle, the last five miles were the roughest ones. I wouldn't do this drive again in a vehicle like this, the rocks along the way are very sharp and could puncture a tire so be prepared for it if you decide to go for it. Also some places of the road are really narrow with little visibility so it can be dangerous if two cars are coming in opposite directions so keep the speed at less than 20 mph. However it was worth all the work and stress of driving through it, the place is absolutely beautiful.<//Review>

<date>1583120755404<//date><review>Echoing nearly everyone else: 4 wheel drive and high clearance vehicles only should attempt this drive. It is about 25 miles ONE WAY of bone-rattling gravel and rock road (remember, it's the same going back). Make sure you have a good spare tire and plenty of fuel.  It may be a while before you get help if you break down, no cell service, so a LOT of water, some food and patience will be necessary. But seeing this is worth it. One of those unique places on the planet where cool things happen.<//review><GmapID>0x80bf60974992ace9:0xfd5de26ead99a77a<//GmapID></record>

< Review>
What can be said that has not already been said about the obligatory drive out to the Racetrack?...  I made the Crosstrek this week and it was a truly amazing experience for photo/video adventure.  I started taking photos of the rocks on my way out to the other side of the Playa.  It's a must see in Death Valley as there is no other place on earth with this type of rock activity. <date>1551498119759</date><gmap_id>0x80bf60974992ace9:0xfd5de26ead99a77a< /gmap_id><Name>Carina Aquino< /Name><rating>5<//rating><Text>(Translated by Google) Just imagine a place where the stones walk. That's right. In Racetrack Playa, stones can crawl. And the most curious thing is that they leave a trail behind, a very interesting thing that usually intrigues researchers, visitors, or rather, anyone who has the pleasure of knowing this place and checking what happened.

Scientists have discovered that this is because a layer of ice forms on the spot, and when it melts, the wind eventually moves the stone, leaving the trail behind. Despite all this, this phenomenon still remains very curious and attracts people from all over the world to see the event.

<Name>Kevin Becker</Name><date>1564876689643</date><rate>5< /rate>< review>
All you can eat shabu shabu with great food and drinks, plus ice cream!

They have a few different choices for broth, my favorites are the sukiyaki and kimchi. They also give you ponzu and a sesame dipping sauce plus eggs if you want.

For meat they have fatty and lean beef plus pork, but I like the beef most.

You can help yourself to unlimited amounts of fresh veggies, rice and other sides plus boba and gourmet sodas.</review>

< text>
This place is okay, taste tends to be on the sweet side but if that's not your preferred flavor spectrum you may want to try the tonkatsu broth. The price is towards the high side and does include mandatory gratuity charge. The all you can eat and drink food is good. Wish the sauces had more variety but I like ponzu sauce as well so it worked okay for me. I came on a monday night at around 6 and had a 1hr15min wait time so safe to expect a wait. There is an 85c bakery near buy if you want to kill some time during the wait. The service was good and made the experience better.</text>

Sadly more hype than anything else. 1 broth is $27.95„ÄÅ2 broth types is $29.95„ÄÅ3 choices of meat„ÄÅand the rest is basically vegetable heaven and thankfully beef curry. I had heard a lot of hype of this place from several people„ÄÅ so naturally to expunge my curiosity I made the 34.3 mile drive down to South Bay. I haven't been in this area for a while„ÄÅapart from leading some Japanese language students to Mitsuwa„ÄÅbut I figured„ÄÅwhat's the worst that can happen? Yeah„ÄÅthis is one of those first and lasts in my book.

The meat quality is fine„ÄÅ the beef curry is decent„ÄÅrice is actually nice. Vegetables are okay-ish a bit wilted than I'd prefer -- keep in mind I came at opening -- but still seems like yesterday's left overs. The broth was pretty bland„ÄÅeven after mixing in a ton of different elements that normally when boiled would change the broth's flavor.

I wanted to like it„ÄÅI really did. But for $29.95 I couldn't handle trying. I strongly believe people give this place more credit than it probably deserves. Just because it's Êó•Êú¨ in a LA Êó•Êú¨Áî∫ of LA doesn't mean it's going to be great. I'm glad I tried it„ÄÅbut I won't be wasting my petrol to come down here.<//Text>

<text>Lunch special is actually very fair. $20 for two plates of meat and access to the ayce curry / vegetables / drinks.
For ayce, you have to shell out $26 per person AND there is a mandatory gratuity charge included. It was somewhere between 12-15% but I can't recall. Was the service worth it? I'd say so.

My gripe with Mo-Mo is that there are only 3 meat options to choose from. Don't get me wrong, the meat quality is actually good. But choosing between 3 can get boring, especially if you're doing ayce. But I'd say the curry made up for it; it's very good curry considering they don't specialize in it.< /text>< Rate>

<Gmap_id>0x80dd4aa495bbb1ef:0xf2612859abf28e7e<//Gmap_id><text>All you can eat shabu-shabu for $30 for 90 mins! A really good hot pot spot that has good service and is pretty prompt. I came here with some friends and ate until we couldn't eat no more!

For the soup selection, we got the Kimchi which is spicy and the Sukiyaki which is on the sweeter side. The combo complemented well with each other! For the veggies, start out with their sampler set and then just get more of the ones you like. The appetizers are okay, but are more of a filler. However, out of the three, my favorite was the Udon Noodle Salad.

For the meats, they are sliced pretty thin so it's hard to really taste the difference so we kept getting rounds of all of them when we needed more. The best side is probably classic white rice, but the ramen is good too. Make sure you heat up the ramen in the hot pot since it comes out cold!

The drinks are about $3 for all you can drink. My favorite was the Jasmine Milk Tea. Simple and a bit creamy from the milk, but really good!

Anyways, try this place out when you want some shabu-shabu time!</text>< resp>

<review>(Translated by Google) Mo-Mo-Paradise is a specialty store that takes "creating the best dining experience for customers" as its belief value, and maintains the authentic Japanese staff spirit from soup base, ingredients, environment and service.
Especially the waiter, the kind and warm temperature, which makes us feel warm and straightening when we have not eaten, it is really great!
Adhere to the freshness of meat and vegetables, and because of the pickiness of the ingredients, nearly 100% of the pots can get a loud name in the market, and there is a constant flow of people every time you eat.
There are four kinds of soup base choices in the restaurant, and the Japanese flavor can only bring the essence of the pot into full play, and the sliced ‚Äã‚Äãmeat slices are simply delicious!
In addition, the sauce in the restaurant is also one of the special features, especially the special "sesame sauce", which has a unique flavor and makes it unforgettable after a long time.
"Crimson Cow": excellent chewy texture with soft and non-dry texture, solid and rich taste, soft and tender meat without gluten, rich aroma after layering, the entrance feels sweet and delicious, yearning!
"Snowflake Cow": The selected Snowflake Cow reveals a fresh, rose-red color, with just the right oil flowers, soft and tender with a slight degree of tenderness, and a slight fragrance and sweetness on the mouth, making people want to stop!
"Pork slices": rich and elegant aroma, fresh and intoxicating taste, specially created to create delicate flavors, natural sweet and light and salty intertwined, the mouth becomes mellow and juicy, charming taste makes people fascinated!
"Various kinds of vegetables and ingredients": Everything is a popular sign. The fresh and sweet taste of vegetables blooms in the pot at a glance. It will definitely make you eat with relish, and you accidentally broke your belly!
After the meal, some desserts or ice creams will be a good ending!
"Milk Tea + Pearl + Coffee Jelly + Lychee Jelly + Red Bean" Q Bouncing Chewy Pearl uses traditional brown sugar to boil slowly and chew while drinking. Taiwan‚Äôs exclusive good taste will definitely make you drink cheeks! But it was too sweet, and the "Count Earl Tea" was inadvertently added. The sweetness was reduced. The sweetness had a crisp flesh taste. The tea was rich in flavor and warm in the mouth. The tea was so fragrant and refreshing!
In the chilly winter, grab a family and friends to try it!

<rate>3</rate>< Text>
Decent spot in the heart of SF.  You actually get a view of Market Street as you enjoy a bite to eat.

Not the most kid friendly place, but that's our own vault for bringing the kid here.  Service was a bit odd as the bartender was our waiter and he seemed out of it a bit, but he was real.  No BS included with his service.  Food is overall pretty good, but expect SF prices with what you get.  The burger was good, but the drinks were fantastic.

SF is the heart of restaurants in the Bay Area and this place does the Bay proud.  Overall, a good experience.</Text>

< review>
Spent from 8/3/18 to 8/8/18 in their inpatient program. The psychiatrist, Dr. Singh spoke to me twice in the 5 days I spent there. Each of the two times lasted less then ten minutes in duration. He incorrectly diagnosed me with a serious mental health issue in that first appointment and prescribed me medication that I informed him I had an adverse reaction to.

On the fifth, I had my hearing to determine whether or not I was fit to be sent home. It was during that time that I learned that the doctor‚Äôs notes about me said I was constantly suicidal and fixating on suicide even though I had been adamant since the beginning of my hospitalization that I had not been suicidal at any time during this ordeal. In that hearing, my patient advocate informed the person overseeing my hearing that I was the third person in a row that day who had notes in their file that were glaringly false. A nurse who had been overseeing my unit during my duration was called in to speak when Dr. Singh was unreachable and she recalled my stay there exactly as I had and I was able to be discharged.

This hospital is nothing but a for profit institution that does not pretend to be anything else once you are admitted. There were no therapists or psychologists on staff to speak to patients one on one. There was just group therapy that dealt with prechosen topics.

This experience meant that I spent 5 days not getting any of the help that I needed and instead was ignored and just given the incorrect medications.

If you have the choice, do not go to this inpatient program it‚Äôs not beneficial at all.</review>

<text>I went here twice..once in April and once in May(i cant remember fully). I remember having a roommate who slept all day and night. Being in the mental facility, there are all different likes of people and crazies, lol. Sometimes the food is good(but i remember i was fasting..which i regret not eating some of the food i would have eaten) if it wasnt for the fact my schizophrenic ways didnt stop me. Plus they force or tell you to eat the food, or you wont be discharged or let go early. Also you u have to do groupings, they have patio time, art time, gym time and the usual of breakfast, lunch & dinner. Plus the lounge..which has a tv, books/magazines and crayons and coloring books etc. Aswel as tea, juice sometimes snacks in the lounge and water. I remember having to do blood test check ups every day/night, they take your heart pressure and etc. I wouldnt mind going to the mental facility again. But im better now and i remember i had trouble sleeping. Plus boredom was a biggie...there wasnt much to do and thats why i wanted to get out already. The most you could do was walk in circles...plus its coed. Still it was a cool experience to look back on. I remember always calling my sisters or aunt all the time(the phone by the lounge). Or seeing the social worker and doctor or whatever to do my check up or to see how long i had to stay there. The first time i went there...i stayed bout a week and the second time i went there, i stayed from Thursday til Tuesday. I was suppose to stay longer than that, but had a court hearing and was able to get out early. You have to do alot of paperwork when getting out though. I have went to another mental facility but i forgot what it was called(that one i stayed for 2 weeks and a half).</text></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
Most terrifying stay in this type of place I ever experienced in my life.  Being as to having a life long struggle with mental issues that are not even close to dangerous to others in any case presented through out my life time I was treated as though I had attempted to assassinate the president or something.
I had not gotten disruptive I followed all the rules,I was social enough ,ate the food, gain all good behavior points available and was friendly as I always am.
The staff had some kind of relentless hatred toward me like a pregidace or the KKK or something that I can't even think of any cause .I'm not even a minority or what ever to have any kind of this to dilude my mental state .
They were very abusive towards me and others that were so very submissive and polite almost as if they couldn't stand friendly smiling people being polite or kind to them.
I am a very nice social person. I believe in knowing names to go with faces and making sure when speaking to a person to state their name clearly so as to confirm acknowledge ment of that conversation with them more personally . They kept saying my name wrong I just politely kept stating the correct way to pronounce it and if they couldn't please use my nickname but was rudely harassed over this and when I stood up to say to a nurse that I would appreciate if she could please stop the rude attitude and not talk in such a sarcastic way and the right way to pronounce my name I was tackled as if I attacked her and strapped  down like Jesus style to a huge concrete slab in a tiny room,where from behind a closed door through a tiny window all the staff stared and laughed at me making fun of me and my name just to harass me some more . After being strapped down for hours without food or water I began to cry and begged them to let me out in which they responded with even more rude laughter and gathered more staff to come to laugh with them,when I escaped from the straps myself and took off out of the room I was tackled and  given injections of some sorts in which I was pretending to be knocked out cold from ,so when they got off I took off running for my life,made it to outside where u ran into some real doctors who seen how freaked out I was and took me In the office to fill out the papers to set me free, I had been sent on false claims of drug abuse and even though I passed drug tests they gave I was still held as a prisoner and it all because I had a siezure of course in which they blamed on the drug abuse that I had tested clean . Now my mental problem is worse then ever I'm paranoid everywhere I go and won't even consider going to a doctor or hospital even when dying of neumonia.
I would rather be sick and die first.
I am scared for my life now. I feel as if I am being laughed at everywhere I go and that people are trying to kill me . I am being stalked daily I am not sure if it had anything to do with the time of this but I do know I was never like this before. I used to love my stays in the hospital and visits with my doctor's for the fact I don't have friends or family to be there for me anymore do to deaths so  looked forward to the friendly doctors n nurses that I would see once or twice a month giving me social contact now I'm never gonna go back to any place that can keep me from leaving or have any control over my meds or food.
I can no longer go and get treated for anything for the fear of being attacked in a brutal or mentally harassing way by people I'm expected to put the trust of my life .
This place and other places like this should be regularly watched for abuse if patients who are incapable of being understood or taken for their word because the lable of crazy that is put on their name most of these patients are not crazy but labeled 5150 anyway so they can't stand up to say for themselves the abuse at the fact their words are cast aside as they are thought to not have the mentality to know what they are saying or must not be understanding the situation correctly.
It's insane that they would hire people to deal with these problems that have no tolerance.<//Review>

<username>Jonathan Madison< /username><Time>1486118409256< /Time><Rating>1< /Rating><Text>TL;DR  Are you looking for an extended stay at inpatient facility where rarely see the light of day, will be treated worse than most prisoners are, and want to kill yourself more than you ever have in your whole life? Then Heritage Oaks Hospital is right for you!

This place is hell on Earth. I implore anyone who may consider putting a family member here or anyone who may end up here involuntarily or voluntarily to seek out any other facility. You will see a psychiatrist for roughly 5-10 minutes every other day. All but a single nurse, treated every patient there like absolute garbage. They ignore you for as long as humanly possible. I even witnessed people having sever panic attacks be completely ignored, even though they are sitting a few feet away with a clear line of site. They have simple lost any compassion or empathy that I doubt they ever had to begin with. You are trapped inside what is basically a hallway. Even with engaging with other patients you will likely find yourself bored, anxious, and claustrophobic the majority of the time due to the lack of stimuli. They offer crayons (continuing the theme of treating patients like incompetent children) but no paper on which to draw or write. You will be blessed with fresh air for some 10 minutes a day in a small, depressing courtyard surrounded my tall, menacing looking fences (it's quite the pick me up). But they don't stop at treating you like the scum of the Earth, they want to keep treating you terribly for as long as possible. All they care about is the hundreds of dollars a day it apparently costs to house the patients. EVERY single patient I was in with on a 51-50, was kept for an additional 72 hours past the legal hold. Why would they stop there if they only cared about money? Because only after six days are patients allowed to receive a Patient's Rights Advocate and actually refute their internment. Need even more examples of their money-hungry ways? One patient I was in with voluntarily checked themselves in, after which they put on involuntary hold, so they could no longer leave. A person who realizes that they should be in a safe environment for a time, then puts themselves into a safe environment was deemed unfit to make decisions for themselves and not allowed to leave when they thought that they were better?! You get a paper stating why you are put on continued hold by the psychiatrist. Most of the time it says some vague, nonsense about being at risk for suicide. Even though most of us bullshitted about how good the facility was and how we were improving so much to get out faster. My favorite reason someone received for staying though was that they were apparently an alcoholic and would relapse.  The funny thing was that person had never drank or done drugs. Either that's malpractice or a complete lack of actually getting to know your patients. Even if this place wasn't after money, they would still be the least caring, understanding, and helpful on the planet. I could go on forever about how bad this place is but to put it simply: If you end up at Heritage Oaks Hospital, YOU WILL NOT GET BETTER. They do not and will not put forth more than the bare-minimum, legal effort to support their jobs. People in medicine should be do it because they love medicine and people, not because it's a stable job. There were one or two RNs or LVNs there that did actually treat us like human beings. It was just such a rare occurrence in that place though; I honestly would not expect it.</Text>< Pics>

<Review>This tour was so awesome! Our guide was Taylor (very awesome and knowledgeable).  Definitely a bucket list item for my wife and I!  This was by far the most interesting tour we have ever been on. You can ask questions about the sets and history of Warner Bros. We really enjoyed not only the guided tour but also the self paced tour near the end. Lots and lots of cool memorabilia from both old and new movies alike. Did not know some of my favorite  movies were filmed right here on a sound stage! Some of the coolest things I have ever seen and had a chance to do. Will definitely come again. Reasonable pricing and easy to find!</Review>< time>

< Text>
Warner Bros Studio Tour
We took LA Go Card which included the Warner bros studio tour. We were greeted by the staff and were allocated different groups for the tour. Following are few main points that you should keep in mind while taking this tour:

- Don‚Äôt expect too much. Everything was shown or explained verbally by the tour guide as we went around the studio on the golf carts.
- It‚Äôll be hot in July, so carry a lot of sunscreen and cap, to stay cool.
- The live sets of FRIENDS & Big Bang Theory was my personal favorite. You can take your cameras/phones and the staff will help you with the pictures too, so no need to worry about rush/crowd.
- There are other attractions too - live size costumes of Harry Potter, Aqua-man & all of Batman‚Äôs automobiles!!
- Try going for this tour on a weekday, you might get lucky and witness some on ground shooting of your favorite shows!
- The staff at every point takes professional pictures too, which you can get printed at the end of the tour for 25$ - which i think was a bit over priced, considering we got the same (and even better) pictures from our phones too so ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
- The tour lasted for around 2-2.5 hours.
- The gift shops pretty amazing but over priced too - if you‚Äôre going around LA and exploring other places too, you can definitely skip buying souvenirs from here.
All in all it was a 8/10 for me! ‚≠êÔ∏è<//Text>

<name>Col Lan</name>< text>
We used the LA Tour Pass to go here and it was well worth it. You get to see the sets of all your favorite movies, as well as archives of costumes and props from your favorite movies. My favorite part was the real set of Friends. Fun fact: not a single episode or scene in friends was actually filmed in New York. It was all on that set. There‚Äôs also a soundstage with all the real Batman vehicles from across the ages. All in all, it‚Äôs wonderful. Be sure to see the iconic water tower too.< /text>

Took my son visiting from NY on the tour today. It was a fun small tour. Wasn't overly crowded and we got to see inside the prop house and the Ellen show stage. It's so interesting how long the studio has been around and some of the original building are still there. DC movies were the best to see. Nothing from BvS or Justice League this time around. Maybe next time. Thanks to our tour guide Paul. Great guy and knows his stuff.</review>

< Text>
We had such a great time here! The tour guide was so knowledgeable and pointed out specific items from movies and TV shows we had seen. It was awesome to see the sets and how they were not brick actually or that the lights, door knobs and other decor were specifically selected and swapped out for each thing they filmed. < review>
The tour was worth it. Our guide was Clint, a very cheery and approy guy that made the experience more enjoyable.

We were taken to the props warehouse, sound stages, sets, and other locations where some of their popular movies and TV shows were shot.

The last leg of the tour is a self-guided one, in the sound stage that was converted to a small museum and souvenir shop. There you can find various articles and paraphernalia of WB movies and shows.< /review>

<review>Loved this tour.Had a great time.. we get to see Harry potter original stuff form movie.. aquaman and wonder women stuff also from original movie...witnessed actual outfits from Aquaman and Harry Potter movies. Worth it for us and already recommended.</review>< Pics>

<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
We had a great tour! Except for not being prepared to spend a lot of time outdoors (bring a jacket regardless of what the weather forecast says). Had a knowledgeable tour guide, got to see some really cool sets, here some great stories about the lots and personnel attached to WB. Definitely would recommend. Parking is simple, uncomplicated.< /Text>

< review>
A little pricey you can record video in doors not outside on the lot. You can take all the pictures you want. Not flash in the indoor areas. Parking was $12 ticket was $68 dollars. I probably should of checked online for a cheap ticket sale by third parties. Overall it was a great experience.< /review>

< Text>
One of the best attraction in Los Angeles. I always dreamt of visiting FRIENDS season set and it finally fulfilled at Warner Brother Studio Tour. We experienced the FRIeNDS set for real and many more like Bat cave where all gadgets and cars used in Batman movies, outfits, Harry potter outfits and props, dc movies costumes for.aqua man, wonder woman etc and outfits for all movies like la la land etc etc.
Here you get a chance to.know how they are using studio in the movies like caesar casino scene in hang over was shooter here; can you believe it.
The guide was really great and told her everything related to movies and sets they have used for different movies.
We even visited sets of Lucifer, Big Bang Theory etc and it was amazing and this tour inspires me a lot.
If you ever visited to la, warner brother studio tour is mustüëåüëå
Make sure you reach early so that you can get parking bear by otherwise you need to spend $15 for parking< /Text>

<rating>4< /rating>< review>
What a fun way to spend the day. I have lived less than an hour away, all my life, and have never taken this tour. I am happy that I finally had the chance. The tour is different per group, based on the tour guide, so you will never get the same tour twice. I loved hearing all the history of the studios. My favorite part was the sound room, where they showed how the sound is created in a movie. Using the movie Gravity as an example.

I would have enjoyed getting off the tram a bit more, which is the only reason for 4 stars instead of 5.< /review>

my friend asked me if i wanted to go to warner brothers studio tour, i didn't realized that they had a tour like universal studio had, so i agreed to go with him, it was great! it was a guided tour and we were give a set period to be in the museum where the props used the movies were displayed,

for a fee you could ride the batpod and appear in a video, you can buy, or if you a a harry potter fan, ride a broomstick. that was fun.i did both and posted them here

i would recommend that you visit at least once with someone who is a Movie Fan.< /Review>

< text>
This was my family‚Äôs third time visiting the Los Angeles area, and our first time at Warner Bros. Studios in my opinion, it is the best attraction in the area, especially if you love movies and television and want to learn more about how they are made. Our tour guide was fantastic. We got to see props from the Harry Potter franchise and Aquaman. We were able to see the ‚ÄúFriends‚Äù and ‚ÄúThe Big Bang Theory‚Äù sets from the shows and take our own pictures on the sets. We walked through the prop house and saw an exhibit of Batmobiles. We saw many sets driving through the lot, and we even saw John Stamos on our tour! This was an amazing experience and I would recommend it to anyone visiting the area. I think any age group would enjoy this.<//text>

< text>
Awesome! I definitely recommend doing this tour!
Our guide was super cool and knew EVERYTHING there was to know about warner bros., their movies, their series and more. We had a great time. The cool thing is that the tour is basically unscripted, so the guide takes you wherever you want to go! It was a wonderful experience and I would definitely do it again!
The only thing I didn't expect was that the friends and big bang theory sets were put into the area where the gift shop is at the end of the tour. They were quite a bit smaller than I expected and were (obviously) crowded.</text>

<Text>The tour is incredible! They take you through actual in use studios and movie/TV show sets. They take you into inventory rooms with props and supplies. Everything is guided for the most part so they explained all areas in detail. Some parts you get out of the tram and walk but most is in a tour vehicle that is open-air.< /Text>< Pictures>

<Text>Loved it. Tour guides were great. Lots to see. Go on a Friday and you stand a better chance of seeing a working set as they generally tape Monday-Thursday. Price is and $72 and $12 to park. The tour takes about 3 hours so street parking isn't an option.<//Text>< Pics>

/user_id><time>1575610864088<//time><rate>4<//rate><text>Everyone who loves to watch movies and tv shows have to visit this place when they are in LA. The tour guide showed us the areas where different movies and tv shows were filmed,like pretty little liars, supergirl, friends. We were fortunate enough to enter a soundstage and it was used to film Lucifer so that was really cool. The best part about this tour is when you get to see the Batmobiles and the Friends and Big Bang Theory sets. You can take a photo on the couch and even if u're travelling alone, the WB staff will help u take a few shots. There is a gift shop and Central Perk cafe that sells actual coffee and food at the end of the tour.

I took away one star from this review because I felt that the tour was too rushed. The tour guide didn't give us enough time to look at the DC and Harry Potter area. We had to quickly walk and take photos. If we lag behind, the tour guide gets mad because he has to complete his tour in 1.5h.  If WB gave a 2.5 h tour, that would be better.<//text>< Resp>

< Name>
Jos√© Mariano D√≠az Duarte<//Name>
<Rating>5<//Rating><userid>100532758791307556355< /userid>< review>
Best Tour ever, so interactive you get to see everything from close sight. Got to enter Hellen's set, Big Bang Theory's set, some locations from very famous films. Our guide was super fun and knew a lot about movies and the studio. The interactive museum is amazing you get to see props from Gravity, Batman, Interstellar, a real Oscar, its too much i can't describe. The souvenir store is very complete, with souvenirs from all your favorite Warner shows and movies. Be sure to bring at least a bottle of watee because it can get a bit hot in the summer.</review>

< Review>
I wasn't sure about this tour when my husband suggested it- how could driving around a bunch of TV and movies buildings be fun? I was so wrong! You get to see some really cool stuff, but the best part was inside scoop on how they make the TV magic. I learned so much and will never look at a TV show or movie the same way again. Our guide, Zach, was super knowledgeable and was able to answer everyone's questions. Very well spent $69. The only downside is you also have to pay for parking which is $15.< /Review>

< review>
Amazing. If you're visiting Los Angeles, you have to do this studio tour. Our guide, Daniel T. was the greatest, big shoutout to him. Ask for him if it's possible, he's funny, interactive and he knows a lot. The tour is long, you'll see the behind-the-scenes of many Hollywood film and TV shows, that's unbelievable. Very recommended.</review>

< text>
Wait for it... and ACTION!
The Warner Bros. Studio Tour is a Hollywood movie studio tour that is just what you wanted.  Television shows, Movies, film editing, working sound stages (right now), post production suites, Eastwood Scoring Stage, interactive museum (just below the iconic WB Water Tower (Yakko, Wakko, Dot are you in there?) and Stage 48.  You can be in an episode of Friends, maybe ride Batman's Motorcycle Batpod, or fly in a "Harry Potter" quidditch match or maybe something else... TBD.  Take a tour and see the cast & crew working on your favorite TV show or a new movie "Coming Soon to a theater near you...".  The tour is amazing and the tour guides, well, they may just be the "hollywood insider" you have been waiting for.  LIGHTS - CAMERA - ACTION - WB STUDIO TOUR ACTION!< /text>

< name>
k</name>
< date>
1574817972873</date>
<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
I took this tour with my family and had a great time. Loved all the costumes and sets. Had a really great tour guide. The photos we got to take on the Friends couch was a highlight for all of us. They recently added the fountain to the lot. We drove by that pretty fast. Also getting coffee at Central Perk was fun.The coffee was really good. The Batman cars were amazing to be near. Getting on and off the small shuttle to check  everything out and walk around the street sets made for a great tour. I learned a lot about how much work goes into getting everything right for a movie scene.
The tour is about two hours but at the end you can stay and take your time getting pictures and videos that you can purchase. Plus theres more props and costumes from movies that you can look at. Also a show on how sound is done in movies. That was really interesting. And of course theres a great gift shop with lots of cool merchandise.
We parked in the underground lot for $15. I did see street parking available too after we had parked.
Overall a great tour to take of you're looking for a studio tour.<//Text>

<GmapID>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988</GmapID>< review>
Really great tour of one of Hollywood's biggest studios.  Tour guide customized the tour for our group.  Lots of great facts and insight about dozens of films and shows. We were able to visit and stand on the set of The Big Bang Theory.  The Warner Bros Archives was very unique, filled with lots of actual costumes and props from numerous movies.  This tour is definitely worth the price and your time.  You won't be disappointed.</review>

<user>117837649947216873925</user>< user_name>
Dilip Kumar Kacher< /user_name>
<time>1528768055762< /time>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< review>
A 45 mins to an hour tour to depict the legacy of Warner Bros. In Hollywood movies. By watching just studios u can imagine how perfectly and finely movies are created. The tour start from studio premises where u could witness famous WB logo in a water tank. Tour representatives explain importance of each places. Followed by DC museum cum studio then other studios where famous talk shows telecasted then prop studios etc and it ended with a studio 12 where friend series set is present along with small snack & coffee shop & merchandise store. You could also witness live series shooting or spot any star.<//review>

<text>We really enjoyed this tour, tour guide Kevin was very likeable and very knowledgeable. Being able to walk around the 'streets' and get a close up look was great & fascinating. The first museum stop had the batman & harry potter costumes and props - very cool. The 2nd stop was the 'batcave'; WOW! to see all those batmobiles in one place just amazing. Then stage 48 with the green screens, friends set was pretty cool. Finished the tour with a latte in central perk. This was a tour, universals tour is more of a ride - make of that what you will.</text>< pics>

< review>
Friends, Harry Potter, Big Bang theory, DC characters like Wonder Woman and Batman - whew, I didn't realize Warner Brothers produced so many iconic stories (in addition to all of their older work).  Be sure to arrive at least 15 minutes early, it will take a while to park and get through security. The tour guides are very knowledgeable and enjoy a lively group with questions.  The guided tour lasts for about 2 hours with several short stops.  You will see costumes and props from Harry Potter, DC characters including several Batman cars and bikes.  We also got to see the Big Bang set which was a pleasant surprise.  At the end of the tour you are turned loose to wander through a few exhibits such as the real Friends set, and a few green screen attractions.  We spent about another hour soaking it all in before heading out.< /review>

< Name>
Amanda<//Name>
<pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM3C9rvVG2fKzOH1Y3HiUo6Vxq2bRkBBaQGWXkQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8R2geVavn_97fIdoGloK2fDPuE9GmvvZ4VY4o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOmR3oi3uKcLR2NoPwrqMPbZUq4ufdKFC4t0Ah8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOqJqs5xQsrPaRcwrbbMg7YmgiMaFNIXGanGbyD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics>< review>
My family had a super fun time on the tour! The tour itself is about 2 hours long and then you can explore a little interactive museum at the end where you learn more about the filming process, can take pictures in some old TV show sets and buy them at ridiculously expensive prices, etc.

While I loved the entire tour, I do wish it went on a little longer. We were rushed through the DC/Harry Potter area so quick I really didn't get to see anything, and all the different groups were crowding so close together I couldn't hear my own guide. I could've easily spent 30+ minutes in that place but we were rushed through in 15 minutes. Same for the batmobile section, which was amazing to see, but we were only given 3-5 minutes to look around a warehouse with about 10 batmobiles in it.

Tl;Dr you should go because you'll have a lot of fun, but Warner Bros needs to give you more time in some of the places.< /review>

<Review>I visited here last weekend and being a DC fan since i was in the fourth grade...this was extremely fun and a dream come true! Though there are no rides on this tour, but if you are a fan of movies in general, this tour is a must for an LA trip as it is super informative!
1. You show up at their office and can park in their office basement; post the initial check in which is super convenient (they have a starbucks inside where you can chill before the tour starts), you board a big cart which can accommodate around 25-30 people which is pretty decent!
2. They show you the iconic WB Water Tower as you enter the studio followed by the sets where a lot of recent and classic movies were shot.
3. You then get to visit Stage 25 which is where Big Bang Theory is shot. This is the only place where you cannot take photos.
4. Also, no videos are allowed during the entire tour except for Stage 48 which comes at the very end of the tour and you can spend as much time as you want there. I took the regular studio tour which they wrapped in 2 hours.
5. Next, you get to spend around 20 min. at the DC and Harry Potter exhibit which are pretty cool. They have all the first issues of Superman, Batman, Aquaman, Wonder Woman, Cyborg, Flash, Justice League and Teen Titans which is cool and one gets to see all the DCEU movie costumes and Harry Potter stuff up close. You can take pictures with the sorting hat as well. There are attendants at this exhibit with whom you can interact for any questions.
6. The picture car vault houses all the batmobiles which is surreal when you see them the first time. The vault is a bit dark so keep your cellphones charged and flashes on. The only bummer when i visited was they did not have the Justice League batmobile which i really wanted to see. Also, you get to spend 5-10 min. here so one has to be quick when taking photos.
7. You finally get dropped off at Stage 48 which is the WB museum where you get to see several movie making aspects, such as, production design, story writing, etc. There are concept arts from some of the 90s animated TV shows (DC animated universe, Looney Tunes) as well. One can hop over the batpod and have their picture taken too. There are hard copies of movie scripts from the 30s and 40s and you can shop at their store for some fun merchandise and memorabilia!
Would highly recommend if one is a fan of DC and a movie buff in general!
Though, they should increase the amount of visitor time at the DC exhibit and the picture var vault!
Would highly recommend and will visit again!<//Review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNQXErb9fTEr2YNA-SYYixxuAQ39PUb4Q5z3vdo=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': <Review>The Warner Bros. Studio in Hollywood offers quite a few tours for fans of their featured films, especially DC fans with their DC Universe: The Exhibit. The exhibit showcases costumes and props used in the movies Wonder Woman, Justice League, and the upcoming Aquaman movie. Fans get to take an up close and personal look at "the intricate details" of their favorite superheroes costumes, according to the Warner Bros. Studio tour website. The Justice League section of the exhibit even has the original comic book issues of each member of the team on display.</Review>< Rate>

<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
My wife and I did the regular tour. It was awesome. Our Tour Guide was Nicole (from NY) and was a wealth of knowledge. She was awesome and provided us with info on movie  magic and how things work. I loved the props and costumes. Since it's a working studio things change over with each set and movie. Wish there was a little more on the classics and more about the Warner brothers themselves and the history of the studio. Love that we were able to walk around "Anytown USA" and not just be in the cart the whole tour. The Friends set at the end was amazing and fun. Overall it was interesting and neat to see were the movies come alive.</Review>

This tour is worthwhile! We were able to go into Ellen's soundstage, see some buildings and houses up close, we also saw batmobiles. Nicole was our tour guide and she was great! Made me crack up a few times, she also worked on Jerry Springer's production team if you have any burning questions about that show.  The tour lasts two hours, then end is a cool museum that goes over different production aspects AND they have the couch from Friends! There's also a gift shop on the other side with cool merch from various shows. I would have stocked up but, my carry-on was stuffed already. Which brings me to another point, you can have your bags/luggage stored, just tell the person at the front desk. They also have an outlet along the back wall on the other side from the Starbucks which is what I'm using now. After so many pictures, my phone battery is barely hanging on. It was mentioned that sometimes actors can be seen during tours or even might join in, sadly it's a Sunday so not much going on except some crew which were still cool to see.<//review>

<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMN5EMQrgXOjBWP73oreOOvizMkicewprdPAnqZ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMJcXUy7_jZSVGqXgz7S2-yVG_mhIdBK75siOjj=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPvsNzFjzPY2d5culT6OKN6ZBhcsrNcmN3ZLZDm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics><time>1527042001754</time><gmapID>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988< /gmapID>< review>
Friends, Harry Potter, Big Bang theory, DC characters like Wonder Woman and Batman - whew, I didn't realize Warner Brothers produced so many iconic stories (in addition to all of their older work).  Be sure to arrive at least 15 minutes early, it will take a while to park and get through security. The tour guides are very knowledgeable and enjoy a lively group with questions.  The guided tour lasts for about 2 hours with several short stops.  You will see costumes and props from Harry Potter, DC characters including several Batman cars and bikes.  We also got to see the Big Bang set which was a pleasant surprise.  At the end of the tour you are turned loose to wander through a few exhibits such as the real Friends set, and a few green screen attractions.  We spent about another hour soaking it all in before heading out.< /review>

My wife and I had an amazing tour here. It was worthwhile spending a whole day. We had a tour first outside seeing many buildings that were used in movies. Then we explored buildings inside, and saw many attractions. Particularly, seeing the Batman-related museum was amazing, seeing the real cars and equipment used in the movie. Definitely recommend for those who love Warner Bros. movies.</Text>

Word of advice: buy tickets ahead of time!

< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNydlU7iktOWeEmOwbXf04t9aU2AEvh3U9bF8Tk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>

<user>112267332700308752805<//user>< name>
Cesar Cantu< /name>
<Time>1567969742428< /Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
Bibi was an awesome tour guide! My kiddo (11 year old girl) and I managed to make it just in time for the last tour of the day (09/06/2019) and were set up with Bibi as our tour guide. We got lucky and ended up in a group of four. I almost didn't do the tour because of some of the reviews saying it wasn't worth it but it definitely was! We got to tour the back lot, which is where they film outside scenes. You end up learning how much you missed in a lot of movies and shows that you've seen. Bibi was full of information, my kiddo had a lot of questions and she answered everything really well. The few things she might not have known she didn't try to fake and it ended up in really good conversation, super genuine. We also toured an actual set, in our case for the show "All American," the prop warehouse, and a few other buildings. All in all it was definitely worth the money. The self guided portion at the end was pretty cool too. Don't hesitate to do it, probably one of the best things we did, definitely better than Universal Studios as a whole.< /Text>

<user>108866392833495062790<//user><username>Jaroslav Madacki</username><time>1592694099916< /time><Rating>4< /Rating>< review>
The Warner Bros. Studio in Hollywood offers quite a few tours for fans of their featured films, especially DC fans with their DC Universe: The Exhibit. The exhibit showcases costumes and props used in the movies Wonder Woman, Justice League, and the upcoming Aquaman movie. Fans get to take an up close and personal look at "the intricate details" of their favorite superheroes costumes, according to the Warner Bros. Studio tour website. The Justice League section of the exhibit even has the original comic book issues of each member of the team on display.<//review>

< time>
1572303582443< /time>
< user_id>
106178523846773641931</user_id>
< review>
This was my first studio tour so I didn't know what to expect but I was pleasantly surprised how enjoyable it was! I'm not a movie/tv buff but I still had a great time. We came here as a team outing so I didn't pay for the tour. The entire tour took almost 3 hours and although you are in a tram, you are also walking a lot so it's especially important to wear comfortable shoes.

Be prepared and bring a hat, sunglasses, comfortable walking shoes, camera, and water bottle! It was very sunny outside and there was only one area where we were able to drink water from a dispenser. We were all very thirsty by the end of the tour! Our tour guide was hilarious and also very knowledgeable. We were cracking up the entire time! There are lots of photo ops so wear something cute! At the end, they have a gift shop with cute apparel, keychains, Harry Potter wands, etc and a Central Perk coffee shop. I recommend going to Ciao Cristina beforehand for lunch since it's only 2 minutes away and the portions are generous.

After the tour, we had a difficult time trying to catch an Uber back since our driver couldn't find us and there were a lot of people catching Uber after the tour. We waited almost 20 minutes and I missed my train! I recommend driving instead since it's easier.< /review>

I really wanted to see Harry Potter Stage or Maybe some Shameless. Shameless bar was closed because of their Horror Events, Harry Potter was very and very bad comparing to WB in London. There was a lot  of DC. And honestly - I don't like it. DC is not good at all comparing to Marvel. So this part was not interesting to me. Next Ellen stage. I don't know what is it so I was not interested also. Overall, I didn't like the tour because I have feeling that they can show us more than they did. No one in our group was interested in DC, but YES, We spent like an 1 hour for DC things ( Looks like they didn't expect that there's some people that not interested in this thing and they did it as "must do"). But again, We was not interested in DC, so why show it to us? At the beginning our tour guide told us: "Expect for a heavy-pictures day". I did 0 pictures. That's how I was interested. Go to UNIVERSAL STUDIO! That's much better!< /Review>

< UserId.>
109890444828455865930< /UserId.>
<username>Tricia Hefner<//username>< Time>
1493695395660< /Time>
< Rating>
4</Rating>
< text>
It cost $12 to park, which was not included in the ticket price. The tour started with a movie to highlight all of the movies WB has made. Then onto the golf cart with 14 people plus a tour guide, who listed which movies were made where as we went along. We made several stops to walk through back lot sets and watch a few more short movies in different rooms of the back lot "buildings." One stop was for their small museum, which included a floor dedicated to DC (Batman, Suicide Squad) and a floor dedicated to Harry Potter. Another stop was for their 75 Years of Batman exhibit, which includes Batman's vehicles. The tour guide pointed out several sites from Gilmore Girls, Pretty Little Liars and Big Bang Theory, such as Lorelai's house and the Stars Hollow gazebo. We saw the set for Big Bang Theory, which was complete and ready for their return to tape the new season. The tour ended with a visit to their larger museum, which includes a replicated Central Perk, a quick look into each step of the filmmaking process, and a gift shop. Overall if was a good tour and an interesting look into the behind the scenes world of entertainment.</text>

<username>JoAnn Genette< /username><Date>1581228207703<//Date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
< Text>
We attended the special Christmas time tour as they redesigned a version of Stars Hollow from Gilmore Girls; the gazebo and town's sign. You can also stand under Luke's diner sign. The house was a gift shop inside. There's a few things which were "off" as far as the decor inside but overall it worked. Living room (which didn't have a monkey lamp) and Rory's bedroom (kinda'). No kitchen. They played songs you'd recognize from the show and certain episodes. The tour guides are great. I don't know the normal routine but they let us enter Ellen's studio while the show was on hiatus. You can take a photo on set as long as you don't step up into the couch area or sit on the couch. There's a few spots on the tour which are just props & costumes so overall it's museum-y like. They take you inside the big prop warehouse which is a hodgepodge of a lot of "stuff" aka props. The Christmas Tour also lets you get up close and personal with the fountain from Friends. There's a photographer on-site who will take your photo and he was nice. I felt bad for him since every single person walking up to him did the friend's theme song clap. He fake smiled and handled it well. The day/night of our visit they were repainting the water tower. That was fun to witness. You can take pics on fake sets for Big Bang theory & the coffee place from Friends which a lot of visitors enjoyed. We didn't want to wait in line. The entire experience takes about 4 hours.<//Text>

< Review>
I loved the tour. I'm also a big fan of several shows/movies filmed at Warner Bros, so that helped. My tour guide (I completely forgot his name, it started with a K) was very knowledgeable and just a funny, great tour guide. I also loved this tour because we got to walk around the sets, go through the prop room, and best of all, sit on a Friends couch. I also came on a day when not a lot of things weren't filming, so my group was able to go into several places and see several things most tours wouldn't get to do! A great thing about the tours is that each one isn't the same. If you do this tour and come back next month, you might see completely different stuff! Although I've only been on one other studio tour, I've researched a lot and I do believe this is one of the best out there. Highly recommend, especially if you're a fan of Warner Bros shows/movies (Friends, Pretty Little Liars, Gilmore Girls, Casablanca, Fuller House, The Big Bang Theory, Mom, Harry Potter, Batman, Shameless, The Ellen Show, etc). Although the gift shop was a little pricey (the reason for 4 stars; I like souvenirs!) I know I will recommend this studio tour, and might even come back some time to do the deluxe option! :)<//Review>

1584408671728<//Date>
<name>Justine Soucy<//name>< user_id>
116456432611149049289</user_id>
<Pictures>None< /Pictures><resp>None</resp><text>Second Studio Tour on our trip! This one I was really excited for because they had Harry Potter, Friends, Gilmore Girls, and the cafe from la la land. It is a 5 Stars because it was an out of this world experience and a once in a lifetime thing for me, but compared to other tours it was a 4 Stars.

You enter the building by the back entrance (make sure to tell your taxi/Uber, we got sent to the wrong Warner Brothers entrance) and you pass security. They have a Starbucks while you wait to be checked in. The tour starts with a little video montage and then you're off to the carts.

The cart seats 3 per row but most of our group was in 2's so we had to split up. Our tour guide was nice but he didn't share the same interests as us so we couldn't really talk about our love for the same movies/series. And if there's one thing you need to know about studio tours, the guide makes it or breaks it.

The Gilmore Girls set was closed because they were setting something up. But we got to see the Ellen set which was cool. The Harry Potter part was mostly props, and I love props but it would've been cool to see a set (I suppose those are in London). I did get sorted by the prop hat though! Gryffindor! The Friends part was mostly Central Perk recreated at Studio 48, which you visit after the tour. You also get to do a green screen shoot on a broomstick for harry potter which is kinda surreal.

They have a lot of superhero stuff so if you're into batman, wonder woman, superman, this is for you! I'm only mildly a fan.

It was cool that you could walk out of the cart and see the fake buildings but without some sort of example of what they were in, it was hard to imagine them being in a movie/series. There were no screens to show us any examples.

We saw the Big Bang Theory set which was cool! But I wish we could've seen it in action instead of all put away. We also couldn't take pictures of it.

Overall, an amazing experience because I had never seen anything from a movie set in my life. But not the best studio tour in LA.</text>< Rate>
4<//Rate>

<Review>This is my review of the Classic Tour I recently took part in. I had my bestfriend join me, and had very high expectations. Typical tour as far as starting in a screening room, getting on the tour car with a dozen other people, etc. We basically saw some back lots where they filmed Annie, the basement where Gizmo was purchased in Gremlins, theater of A Star is Born with Judy Garland, and other stages. We then went through the props stage, a very cool Batman area, with all the Batman  vehicles. Finally ending in a building with the Cafe from Friends, and other interesting artifacts and Hollywood costumes. I even got to hold an Oscar! It wasn't bad, I just feel that we didn't truly get the 'Classic experience', and we both stated to one another that we actually felt a bit depressed by the tour. Though our tour guide was wonderful, thank you.< /Review><user_name>SEBASTIAN'S SCRIPT<//user_name>< Gmap_id>

<text>Good, but overpriced and disorganized. The cost to content ratio was off here as the tour was relatively short and lacking in interesting items, at least compared to other studios and it often felt more like an advertisement and less like a tour of a studio rich in cinematic history.  That said, our tour guide as pleasant and knowledgeable, and there was enough information to stay entertained, but I am not sure that it justified the price, again compared to other studio tours and parks.</text><Pics>None</Pics>< Resp>

< userid>
108929030660142594237<//userid>
< username>
Lawrence< /username>
<date>1587363926036< /date><rating>2</rating>< Review>
It's just okay. Tour was advertised as 2 hours guided + 1 hour self guided but the guided portion ended early at 1.5hours. The only reason the self guided portion takes an hour is because of queues and queues and queues for photos in the self guided photo op area. We were through the whole thing in under 2 hours.

We took the 5pm tour on Christmas period so it was dark and too dark to see most things. We saw a number of fake streets while being on the electric cart, and two working sets (Conan and Mom), along with fixed exhibits for Aquaman, wonder woman, and Harry Potter. Friends and Big Bang Theory are permanent self guided exhibits are only partial incomplete sets meant for photo op. You can't really walk through them.

We felt rushed through the guided exhibits portion, and the tour guide was not very knowledgeable with questions.

Comparing this and the universal studios studio tour within the theme park, that is far, far, far better. You actually see a number of effects in practice and their sets are much more impressive (including a full sized crashed jetliner), and it includes some 3d rides which are just fun. They also show you clips of the movies when you're passing or stopping by the set - so you can see what movies they're from and where you might recognise the set from.

Warner Bros charged $72 for their tour, I felt it was worth about $30. If you're having difficulties choosing between the two, absolutely go for Universal Studio tour and give this a skip. You won't be missing too much.<//Review>

<UserId.>111446563580895157804<//UserId.><Name>Mina<//Name><Date>1537189880651< /Date><Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
It was a very well organized tour. From start to finish, everything ran like clockwork.

The backlots and sound studios were very interesting. It is really fascinating to see how many shows they make from the same sets. It is a glimpse into how movie magic happens.

I enjoyed the Friends set, even though I didn't care much for the show. I also liked seeing everything DC.

Depending on what they are filming at the time governs what you will see. Even the tour guides are surprised by how the sets change so rapidly.

I went to Paramount and Universal as well, but Warner Bros was the best of the lot, with Paramount second.

If you are a movie buff or enjoy TV series, it is worth seeing.<//Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating><text>Excellent place for fans!! Totally worth the money. The tour runs in small groups of 12-14 people in a golf cart for most part. The guided portion runs for about 2 hours but the time just flew by. The tour guide takes us through many exterior locations and some indoors. Pictures were allowed everywhere except the actual sets. < text>
I grew up hanging for this tour. It's relatively polished and a bit of thought into it but considering the deep, rich history of Warner Bros - it disappointed me in how it's run. If you like Harry Potter or DC then this is for you. If you like the say 50,000 other WB productions of TV and Film from the studio then you get dribs and drabs.

Our tour guide was peppy (they all are) but her knowledge was a bit off and she made a lot of mistakes throughout with her trivia and info. I assume she thinks everyone is dumb enough to just listen to everything and take her word as credibility.

It was nice to do the outside tour although she missed certain parts which are advertised and also other tour groups were going to it so you get a mixed match of venues and locations.

That costume section is woefully underwhelming as it's focused only again on DC and Harry Potter. Yawn.

The set visit was exciting but we went to Lethal Weapon a show which I said to our tour guide was about to be cancelled and she had no clue about the show so it seemed like a tick off a box rather than something memorable. We also couldn't walk around the stages like Sony allows which was disappointing. I really wanted to see all the plaques at each studio stage but instead we all heard about DC...DC...DC...DC...

The last section is cool to an extent but our tour guide promised things that couldn't happen like holding an Oscar etc.

The gift shop was good though.

It was definitely worth it but I left disappointed and in no hurry to come back. Again they should have 2 types of tours - one for the tourists who just want a standard no-frills tour and one for those who want some industry inside Hollywood. When I had more info than our tour guide it leaves a bit of an underwhelming feeling.</text>

< review>
My husband and I thoroughly enjoyed this tour. We could not stop talking about how awesome our tour guide Javi was. We really appreciated his knowledge, upbeat personality, and great sense of humor. We are both huge movie buffs and for being our first time doing a studio tour, we had an overall great time and learned a lot. We got to see where scenes from many famous movies we're shot such as Spiderman, Jurassic Park, the Nun, Gremlins, The Mask, Ocean's 11, Annie, and from popular tv shows such as Pretty Little Liars, Gilmore Girls, Friends, Desperate Housewives, Big Bang Theory and much more. We got to walk around a real working sound stage, as well as see props from the movies HP, Batman, and Aquaman. Staff was overall very friendly. The tour took about 2 hours, but it roughly depends on you since a small portion of it is self-guided. If you sign up, see if you can have Javi be your tour guide. Thank you Javi and WB Studios for a great experience :)<//review>

< review>
Yesterday afternoon my wife and I took Bobs tour by recommendation of a friend. During our tour, we stopped in front of a famous house where a very well known actor of a recurring sitcoms was sitting on the steps. Bob proceeded to say his name loudly. You could tell the actor was trying to be discreet, wanting privacy and when the actor would not acknowledge our tour guide, Bob hopped out of the vehicle. Bob then began dancing and singing near him to draw attention. The actor looked mortified even holding his hand in front of his face and I thought it was completely disrespectful. At the end of our tour Bob then asked in English and Spanish that is a must to tip your tour guide. My husband and I declined due to his antics and Bob let us know he was upset. It‚Äôs safe to say we will ask for anyone other than Bob on our next trip to Los Angeles. The tour scenario in itself was great! The tour guide not so much!
We do give 4 ‚≠êÔ∏è‚Äôs  to actual visual of all we experienced with from our favorite movies to tv shows. As far as Bob unfortunately we give zero ‚≠êÔ∏è‚Äôs for his unprofesionalism.<//review>

< review>
Had a three hour tour. 2 hours guided, and 1 hours free walk through a large amount of movie and TV show props, sets, and experiences. Our Tour guide was Anna, who was very well spoken and easy to get a long with. She seemed knowledgeable on both Warner Bros. and other film/TV facts. We were able to explore the Conan and Mom sets/stages as well as a variety of other sets and scenes not currently in use. The tour consisted of both walking and riding in an electric cart. It was always easy to hear our guide as they are small groups tours.< /review>

<user_id>118156018798278680947< /user_id><Name>Zoe Polk</Name>< time>
1541377230673</time>
<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
This tour was a great experience! One of the best "tourist" attractions that I have been on, in fact it felt more like a true experience than a tourist attraction. Guides are able to take you to a number of different sound stages and back lots. Do your research and know what is filmed at this studio, they are happy to take you to any stage that interests you! We saw Lucifer, Ellen, and Big Bang Theory. It is nice that the guides are given freedom, and there is no specific tour.

The supervisor of Lot 48 is such a gem (Vanessa?). We were on the trolly back to the parking lot, and mentioned to her that we wished we would have seen more Gilmore Girl stuff, and she stopped the cart to give us a personal walking tour of the Midwest backlot (which was passed over by our original tour guide). She had a lot of fun facts for us and helped us feel very welcome on set!

Would certainly recommend to friends who are visiting LA, and would consider going for a second time next time I'm in town! We went on a Sunday,  which meant there was no filming and we had access to nearly the entire studio. It would also be interesting to go on a weekday and see it as a working studio.< /Text>

< review>
I liked the part of the tour where we got to go in and see the sets. Got to see friends and Big Bang theory set.  The rest of the tour was a little boring as they just take you around and show you some streets and few properties from outside for the movies which are really old. It‚Äôs hard to connect to places like that. I was expecting to see sets for some current or not so old shows or movies. For the price you would expect a much better tour. I would suggest to Warner brothers to include things what most of people would relate or connect to and not just take people around showing them empty streets and some infrastructure that was used many decades ago. It seemed as if the tour has been created in the area which is hardly being used by Warner Brothers. It‚Äôs like you are visiting Warner brother Studio which has been created just for the tour and not the actual studio.</review>

norman brooks</user_name>
<Time>1532813790745</Time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<Review>Pt1 April 2017. Warners used to top our list, and it's not be missed, but us film buffs can really get down into the weeds at Paramount. Like at Warners, no two tours are the same at Paramount due to activities always changing on the lot. At Paramount you will mix more closely with crews prepping for projects. You won't see any actual filming, except maybe at a distance, but you will see staff in motion and equipment in place and sets. All good stuff. Lauren was the guide this trip and she was tops. Really knew her stuff and tons of movie minutiae. Upon entering the studio I was greeted by Austin who made me feel genuinely welcome and that I was a valued guest. If you are into film and can only go on one tour, pick Paramount. Note: Universal is a complete waste of money and time.
Pt2 April 2018. VIP Tour. And this tour, parking is free saving you $12. The parking lot is right across the street from the tour entrance on Melrose Ave. After After entering the building you‚Äôll be immediately greeted by a security officer. Cynthia, working security that morning, was fast and professional. ( pretty, too) Next was meeting Bridgett Who got the signed in and gave me my Paramount ID badge. And she took our drink orders. No liquor, though. Next, our guide for the day, Bob, greeted us and after introductions were made amongst the VIP visitors. Bob next took us out onto a cart and we began the day‚Äôs journey to seeing the movie business up close. Bob was most knowledgeable. I‚Äôm knowledgeable about the movie business but his vast knowledge put mine to shame. I learned a lot from him. This tour is actually very much behind the scenes. We talk to people in carpentry, graphics, restoration, construction, and all of the things that go into making a film. The studio provided lunch in the lunch theater lobby. It was not much of a lunch compared to the lunch served on the Warner tour unless you‚Äôre into eating like a rabbit.The afternoon was occupied by visiting soundstages while set up for productions, we‚Äôre not actually in use during the moments we visited. It would have been nice to see an actual project being film or TV program being taped, but the reasons for that are understandable. At the end of the tour we were given a souvenir photo of ourselves and our choice of one sheets for movies that had not even been scheduled for release. That was very cool. Is it worth the extra hundred plus dollars for the VIP tour? Absolutely! That is, if you want to get a good 5 1/2 hour dose of how movies are really made.<//Review>< Pictures>

<Review>Had a great time! Tour was around 3 hours as stated and our tour guide Carissa was great! She asked the group (about 10 people) what we were most looking forward to and geared the entire tour based on what we were interested in. Money was very well worth it. We were able to see how the studio works and see the sound stages (unfortunately no photos allowed). <resp>None</resp><Name>Zoe Polk< /Name><Text>This tour was a great experience! One of the best "tourist" attractions that I have been on, in fact it felt more like a true experience than a tourist attraction. We saw Lucifer, Ellen, and Big Bang Theory. It is nice that the guides are given freedom, and there is no specific tour.

The supervisor of Lot 48 is such a gem (Vanessa?). Would certainly recommend to friends who are visiting LA, and would consider going for a second time next time I'm in town! <time>1535130859185< /time>< Review>
Warner Bros. Studio Tour Hollywood is a public attraction situated inside Warner Bros. Studios, Burbank close to Hollywood and part of the greater Los Angeles area. It offers visitors the chance to glimpse behind the scenes of one the oldest and most popular film studios in the world over a two to three hour period.

The studio tour in some form has been open for several decades, but it was recently renamed to give the Warner Bros. Studio Tours a more uniform identity after the success of Warner Bros. Studio Tour London in Leavesden. Previously it was known as the Warner Bros. Studios VIP Tour.< /Review>

This tour was pretty good. The tour guide seemed knowledgeable but since their tours are unscripted, it seems that with a different tour guide you would have heard different (and perhaps more interesting, depending on what you like) facts  - at least, from what I overheard as our cart passed other carts. <user_name>Maya Autret<//user_name>< time>
1531257574137<//time>
<rate>4< /rate>< text>
Overall, a fun experience. They make it easy to check in, people are friendly, and there is a Starbucks while you wait. Once on the tour, you get in and out  of the car, walk through sets, and get fun facts about shows& movies filmed onsite. There are also quite a number of fun exhibits, such as Super Heroes (e.g., Wonder Woman), Harry Potter, Batman's cars (actual cars - very cool), clothing from old favorite movies such as Casablanca. We saw the sound stage for the Big Bang Theory, and got a better idea of how the shows are produced. There is also an interactive portion, where you can ride a Harry Potter scene against a green screen, and they take photos/videos that you end up buying for stupid money at the end. But like I said, the people make it all very fun and nice. Just one note about the tour guide, sometimes they go very fast and drone on like robots as they herd one group after another. It feels more tired than exciting at times. But overall, worth the time and money.< /text>

<rating>3< /rating>< Text>
Nice, but a bit boring tour. The tour includes driving through the streets used for filming, looking inside empty house used for filming. Then we visited a sound stage for the Big bang theory show, which is nice only if you are big fan of the show. We had 10 minutes to look at the Batman cars and take pictures, and then short walk through the old films storage. The last part is a self tour of stage 48, which is very commercial - you can have a picture / video taken of you in film like spot and pay to get the picture /movie.
Kids enjoyed the tour, while the adults felt a bit bored.< /Text>

<rating>1< /rating><Text>I booked this tour for my parents for their first ever trip to Los Angeles, as my parents really wanted to see what goes on behind the scenes at a working studio. Ultimately decided on Warner Studios because it was the most pricy option - so must be good!

Worst decision ever - tour guide was not the least bit interested in her job and did not even try to explain anything more a one liner sentence each time. Could see that she was just waiting for time to pass for the end of the tour the minute it started. It got so bad that one of our fellow passengers even decided to secretly leave our group to join another one as the tour guide was basically just wasting everyone‚Äôs time. (He was forced to join back our group unfortunately for him).

It was such an utterly disappointing experience. My parents were really looking forward to this for many weeks now, and it‚Äôll probably be their only chance in life to visit a working studio. Although we did pay a lot of money to travel to Los Angeles and to attend this tour, what hurts us the most is that it wasted so much of our time here, when we could have visited any of the other studios around. It might be just a normal day at work for her, but it was supposed to be a dream trip for my parents.

Our advice: Skip this studio and choose any of the other wonderful studios available in Los Angeles. You might be luckier than us and get a good tour guide, or you might also get what we got - a bad experience. Your holiday time is precious, so why even bother risking it here?<//Text>< Pics>

<Rate>4<//Rate><review>Awesome experience. It was really cool to see how they are able to manipulate the sets to look like completely different places. The tour focused a lot on Pretty Little Liars and Friends. We were able to see Ellen's set and we were also able to take photos on the Friends couch and the Big Bang Theory couch. The major disappointment was that there was almost no Scooby Doo merch in the gift shop! My younger sister and I went to Warner Bros. specifically because she is probably the world's hugest Scooby Doo fan. All they had was a hat with a little Scooby outline on it and some candy that said "Scooby" on them. (Scooby Snacks if you will.) All in all, this was a really great experience and I was in awe after seeing how it is all done with such a small amount of space.
