Ashley H<//name>
<Time>1501513327987<//Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
This three hour experience provided a behind the scenes look at a real studio and some of the props that were used in popular movies and television shows. Unfortunately we did not see any live filming, but our tour guide was constantly providing us with information about the indoor and outdoor sets. We saw the set of The Big Bang Theory and a town that is repurposed for many television shows. While I wish we could have seen filming and more actual sets instead of props, we had such a good time that I had to give this place five stars.<//Review>

<Review>Took the tour, well worth it. This is a more traditional tour, not a ride or gimmicky drive by. A lot of history to be seen and a tour guide who knows there stuff. <user_id>102393726692029821340< /user_id><Name>Michael Watson</Name>< date>

< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<Text>We came here twice a few days apart. On the first time, which was a weekend, we did the VIP tour. The weekend meant that we could go on the sets of weekday shows like Ellen, but you can't walk through muh of the prop department, and the whole site seems quiet. The VIP tour was fine, and well worth the money, but you miss out on a lot as well, such as not being able to walk around and take photos of the city streets that you know from movies and TV. The second visit was for the Deluxe tour, and was on a weekday. The Deluxe tour was expensive, but totally worth it. Our guide Thom was extremely knowledgeable and took us everywhere. We were able to walk all the city streets, taking great photos while he told us every TV show that's ever shot there, even explaining the episode and how they filmed it - it was so interesting and amazing. We were able to visit 3 sets currently in use, including major shows like the Big Bang Theory and Pretty Little Liars, and he explained all about the props and movie making techniques used there. We were even lucky enough to see a few stars, which was cool, and the complimentary lunch was delicious. If you're a fan of any Warner Brothers TV shows that are filmed in LA, you'll find it a thoroughly enjoyable tour, and well worth the Deluxe price tag! We had a totally wonderful experience on both tours, so even if you can't afford the Deluxe tour, the VIP tour is still very much recommended.</Text>< pics>
None</pics>

< Review>
This place is well worth a visit, the guides tailor the tour to which shows and movies the tour guests love and they do a great job explaining everything. The tour lasts a few hours so you can either eat at a Cafe nearby or at the 'Friends' Central Perk Cafe. Definitely recommend looking ahead to see whether you can attend a full day's taping of a TV show.</Review>

<UserId.>113347880767639199061<//UserId.><time>1554090571795<//time><gmap_id>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988<//gmap_id><review>Basic tour price: $69 per adult plus or minus some add ons. Parking in the studio tour garage: $15 flat rate. Take the elevator to ground floor and turn right there will be a metal detector/bag check. You check in and they give you laminated cards with letters on them and then you wait around for them to call out those letters. Theres a starbucks and restrooms while waiting which was like 5-10 min. The tour starts with a short video by ellen DeGeneres about Warner bros and then the tour guides will come take you on a long golf cart thing. Be prepared to walk around quite a bit. The guide stopped at different locations and we walked around. At the end theres a self guided tour portion where rude staff members will cut you off while trying to take pictures after standing in line. Other than that our tour guide was super nice. They are very particular about where you can take pictures or touching things etc so pay attention to that.< /review>< name>

For anyone who loves TV this is a must do tour. We went on a rainy day so it wasn't too crowded. The guides are very friendly and they let you take your time with photos. Every staff member was beautifully polite and generally happy. The studios were very clean and getting from one place to another was extremely easy. < Name>
Jane Anderson< /Name>
<Date>1408686139513< /Date>< Rate>
2</Rate>
< review>
After going to Universal the day before, it is fairly easy to compare, and highlight the differences.  In short this tour has little personality, and almost no "meat" on its bones.

The tour starts with a very well orchestrated video presentation... the person introducing the video had no energy, and sounded completely board of her job... After talking to my daughter, she felt the same way, but both hopeful, the tour guide would be better.... Not to be the case.

We started off by a very lack luster tour of the back lot. The tour guide presented the information with no personality, and little if any enthusiasm for the facts.  I think our whole tram felt headphones would have been more informative.... Then we got dropped off for 25 minutes at a very small Batman and Harry Potter museum.... So, tour so far is 1 hour since we arrived... 10 minute intro, 15 minutes driving through the back lot, and 25 minutes in a museum (that needed 10-15 at the very most).  Why do I say that.. 4 tour groups were all huddled at the entrance waiting to get out of the micro museum...  Then another 15 minutes in another Batman museum of Bat Cars.. (that I think I've seen in at least 2 or 3 other places for the most part, but not all)

Then on to what would should have been the good stuff.. right?  Live studios... Well, we did walk through the working sets, which was really interesting.  Its just too bad that the guide couldn't muster enough energy or enthusiasm to get us engaged in what we should have been immersed in.

By the time we got back to the gift shop, 8 out of 10 of the people on the tour literally were so disinterested they didn't even care to follow the tour guide back in through the shop.  (seriously)...

I wish Warner Brothers would take a lesson from Universal, and make the tour personal, and informative, and fun for goodness sake... it just wasn't any of that...  It deserved 2 stars.. why? ...... Because the tour was just below average, not terrible...

If you only have 1 day to do a studio...consider all the options... I'm not sure I would choose this one again, or even recommend it.</review>

< user_id>
108558469372745048839</user_id>
< text>
This tour was okay at best. I'm going to share with you something I wish someone would have warned me about before you spend the money.

DO NOT GO ON A WEEKDAY! I know it may not work with your plans, but if you want to see anything even remotely cool, you have to go on a day when there's no filming being done. Monday through Friday everyone is working so soundstage visits are very unlikely.

The tour is advertised as three hours, which is technically true, but only after visiting ONE soundstage, the batman car room, a prop warehouse, the DC/Harry Potter props, and the self-guided Stage 48 or whatever, where there's even more props, and a paid green screen photo-op (trap). This not a really a tour, for half of it you are your own tour guide!
No other soundstages, no exterior lot. Save your money!

Unless you are obsessed with Friends, Harry Potter, or DC, skip and wait for the weekend or pass all together.< /text>

<Review>According to Webster, a tour guide is defined as: a person who takes people on trips through an area and explains the interesting details about it.

Our tour guide demonstrated none of the above actions and exhibited none of the above traits, showed no interest, provided no additional information and demonstrated zero enthusiasm. I am not sure why he is in the business he is in, but he singlehandedly torpedoed this entire experience for us which is sad because we were really looking forward to it.

I  also wanted to make sure I was not crazy, and asked a fellow traveler who was a stranger what he thought of our tour / tour guide performance and he confirmed "this is truly awful."

There were some interesting sights and stops but overall, it was hard to get past this tour guide who had nothing to offer. I actually overheard other tour guides and tried to jump ship to their tours BUT our guide did make sure to frequently count our group to make sure no one escaped, when all I really wanted to do was escape.

If there is anyone at warner brothers out there listening, I would love to talk more about this.

<user_name>J T<//user_name><gmapID>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988<//gmapID><Pics>None< /Pics>< date>

< review>
This is an enjoyable tour and the time quickly passes as one discovers the nooks and cranny of what, how entertainment is filmed and produced. We are lucky because we had a great tour guide who took great care of us and really knew his stuff providing great behind-the-scene stories and intriquing tales about many productions. However, this may not be consistent as we noticed other guides who are quite quiet.

Apparently the tour is different on different days depending on what is filming and therefore where you get to go to. We managed to get to the stage set for the big bang, the prop storage in the backlot, WB arhives, a drive through the exterior sets, and the final stage that has the central perk cafe and the gift shop.

Although there is a more expensive tour that we have not experienced, this tour on its own is more than sufficient giving us a causual bird‚Äôs eye view of the world behind the scenes. Some parts were more memorable and unfortunately, because it is studio specific you will not see everything in the cinematic universe. Since WB is DC comics home, there is a lot of emphasis there (but of course) e.g. batman.

Definitely worth a look. For those who are coming to this place it is easily reached via public transport and its nice to walk around the vicinity. We found a host of dining options nearby.< /review>

<Review>Basic tour price: $69 per adult plus or minus some add ons. Parking in the studio tour garage: $15 flat rate. Take the elevator to ground floor and turn right there will be a metal detector/bag check. You check in and they give you laminated cards with letters on them and then you wait around for them to call out those letters. Theres a starbucks and restrooms while waiting which was like 5-10 min. The tour starts with a short video by ellen DeGeneres about Warner bros and then the tour guides will come take you on a long golf cart thing. Be prepared to walk around quite a bit. The guide stopped at different locations and we walked around. At the end theres a self guided tour portion where rude staff members will cut you off while trying to take pictures after standing in line. Other than that our tour guide was super nice. They are very particular about where you can take pictures or touching things etc so pay attention to that.< /Review><username>Sruthi Sanku</username>< Date>

Its kinda boring. I really thought studio tours would be different. All you do is drive around on a trolley and have someone point at buildings and say.. "Such and such is filmed in that building"... The coolest was seeing the Batman cars and Walking through the prop department... But our guide rushed us through.. The nicest people were the check in desk and the Sorting hat handler... Everyone else almost seemed to hate the public..

< Text>
This tour I was looking forward to and it didn't disappoint. You first start by watching a small video about the tour told through the actors from different movies. Then you are assigned a tour guide and they take you to the tram.

There was a lot of pretty little liar sets because they were preparing for filming, but we got to see the house from full house, Merlot's from true blood, the T-Rex chase scene from Jurassic park.

We got to visit an interactive museum, the first floor was all Batman vs Superman outfits, along with Suicide Squad outfits, upstairs had harry potter props.

Hopping back on the tram we saw many movie studios that were used in several movies. The growing pains house, The precinct from Mike and Molly.

We were allowed in 1 sound studio and saw where they filmed the big bang theory. Unfortunately they did not allow us to take any pictures which was a bummer. We then were taken to an indoor studio where we saw all the bat mobiles. Afterwards we were taken to the friends set (Central Perk), where we got to take pictures on the couch, the two and a half men set, a museum full of props from several movies and shows, you can take a picture with an Oscar, There was a bat mobile and a harry potter broom with a green screen that put you into the movie (this gets crowded unfortunately and I was unable to do it :( .

The tour leaves you in an expensive gift shop where you can shop or exit to a tram that takes you back to the front of the tour to your car.</Text>

<Name>Christopher Parker-Swain< /Name>< time>
1461797414398<//time>
<Rate>5<//Rate><Text>Such a fantastic tour! I would definitely do this again!

Just to start out before you loose any attention reading: look around for coupon codes - they are out there and will save you money! :)

To start I recommend getting there a little early, you can look around the gift shop and get some ideas of what you want to buy after your tour. I recommend buying things afterwords so you don't have to worry about lugging a shopping bag around while you are on your tour.

Don't forget your camera on this tour too!! They allow you to take pictures during most of the tour; you never know who or what you are going to see. What is great about this tour is the guides are completely 'go with the flow'. They are fantastic and totally not scripted and boring. Be sure to mention your favorite shows and they will do their best to show you their filming locations, sets (if they still are around), and even possibly items from the show. They take you through a great majority of the lot itself, this includes: facades, the main prop warehouse, possible a set of a show (we saw Pretty Little Liars and the old Friends set), and a set of many cars from tv shows/movies that have been filmed. Also, you get to go into their museum which is awesome, sadly no photography inside here though. During our tour we also got to see them filming both an episode of Pretty Little Liars as well as Mike & Molly.

All in all it was $100 for 2 people and was totally worth it! Our tour was just under 3 hours and we definitely got our monies worth! I highly recommend it for anybody that is interested in film, or anything Hollywood for that matter! Be sure to bring your camera and money to hit up that gift shop after your tour.

PS... they do have a Starbucks inside the gift shop in case you need anything to drink before/after the tour. Enjoy! :)</Text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
< resp>
None<//resp>

Unless you absolutely love Gilmore Girls and Pretty Little Liars, it's pretty boring.  You first visit the backlot outdoor sets mostly to hear about the Gilmore Girls and Pretty Little Liars. Then you drive around the sound stages.  Once again, mostly to hear about GG and PLL.
Visited the sound stage for the series Lucifer which was very uneventful.

< Text>
This tour is all about the studios: you'll wander through the buildings and the sets on a small open train while your guide tells you anecdote and curiosities.
You'll occasionally get off to explore some selected sets and locations.
We went on the set of The Big Bang Theory, wandered in some "Generic american city" sets where they shot spider man and other big blockbusters and learnt a lot about this huge factory of dreams.
Would not bring kids, even though there is a short (20 minutes) visit to the Harry Potter floor of the costume museums that is surely entertaining.<//Text>

< text>
Such a fantastic tour! I would definitely do this again!

Just to start out before you loose any attention reading: look around for coupon codes - they are out there and will save you money! :)

To start I recommend getting there a little early, you can look around the gift shop and get some ideas of what you want to buy after your tour. I recommend buying things afterwords so you don't have to worry about lugging a shopping bag around while you are on your tour.

Don't forget your camera on this tour too!! They allow you to take pictures during most of the tour; you never know who or what you are going to see. What is great about this tour is the guides are completely 'go with the flow'. They are fantastic and totally not scripted and boring. Be sure to mention your favorite shows and they will do their best to show you their filming locations, sets (if they still are around), and even possibly items from the show. They take you through a great majority of the lot itself, this includes: facades, the main prop warehouse, possible a set of a show (we saw Pretty Little Liars and the old Friends set), and a set of many cars from tv shows/movies that have been filmed. Also, you get to go into their museum which is awesome, sadly no photography inside here though. During our tour we also got to see them filming both an episode of Pretty Little Liars as well as Mike & Molly.

All in all it was $100 for 2 people and was totally worth it! Our tour was just under 3 hours and we definitely got our monies worth! I highly recommend it for anybody that is interested in film, or anything Hollywood for that matter! Be sure to bring your camera and money to hit up that gift shop after your tour.

PS... they do have a Starbucks inside the gift shop in case you need anything to drink before/after the tour. Enjoy! :)<//text>

<rating>5<//rating><userid>102073705942918921867</userid><GmapID>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988<//GmapID><user_name>Nigel Antonio< /user_name><response>None</response>< Text>

<pics>None<//pics><Date>1464332110745</Date></record></dataset><record>
<rating>5< /rating><Time>1514575831363<//Time>< review>
My family and I have gone on this tour quite a few times, the most recent being yesterday.  The fact that we have gone on this tour multiple times is an indication of how positive that we feel about it.  That said, it also gives us perspective on how the tours can vary in quality.  Ultimately, it is all about the tour guide that you get.  Some are great and others are not as much. In many cases, you can see a clear difference in the guides who love what they do vs the ones who have studied the tour script and are going through the motions a bit.

The tour that we went on yesterday was very clearly rushed and we avoided several areas of the studio that we could see other tours visiting.  In total, the tour portion itself was only about 90 minutes, which is much shorter than usual.  I have noticed on the last few tours that we have gone on that they have cut back on the amount of soundstages that are visited.  (It has pretty much just been one visited on the last few tours, but used to be 2-3 per tour)

Plus, I just have to say it.  Though I get that it is a popular show, some people don‚Äôt like the Big Bang Theory.  I mention this because it seems to be the # 1 production that is pushed on the tour these days. When the tour visited more sound stages, it was fine to visit the BBT set, but when that is all that you get, it is a definite bummer if you don‚Äôt watch or care for the show. On our tour yesterday, only one person when asked, acknowledged liking the BBT and we heard several guests from the UK say that they didn‚Äôt even know what the show was. Regardless, it was the only soundstage that we visited and much of the tour commentary was focused on the show.

The Studio48 feature at the end of the tour is great, but lately, it seems to be a means for some tour guides to cut back on the actual tour portion and that is a shame.  Plus, I do think that the actual history of the studio should play more into the overall tour experience. I understand that modern audiences would prefer to predominantly hear about Gilmore Girls and Friends, but the history within these walls is staggering. Ultimately, all that said, I went on this tour for the first time 27 years ago and through all of its growth, I continue to love it.  It would be great if all of the tour guides showed the same commitment and that each tour was equal in length and quality, but I also know that is a tough thing to manage or guarantee.  Regardless, this is an absolutely great studio tour and on top of all that it offers, just driving around the historic lot is worth the price of admission alone.  When you get a great tour guide, the experience is second to none.< /review>

<user_id>103072189270868803736</user_id>< name>
Life is Better On Vacation< /name>
<time>1429804083408<//time><rate>5</rate>< Review>
We loved seeing the places where so many of our favourite TV shows and movies were made.  Whether you were paying attention or not you have seen these sets in countless films.  From the original Gotham City Hall to Mrs. Deagle's house in Gremlins. From Hazzard County to the ER hospital bay.  From Kermit's swamp to the theatre where Sheldon steals Raiders of The Lost Ark.  From...  The list goes on and on.  We sat on the couch from Friends and visited The Big Bang Theory & Pretty Little Liars sound stages.  Try to take as many pictures as you can as a little research will reveal that some movie or show you love came to life in that very spot.</Review>

< Review>
We loved seeing the places where so many of our favourite TV shows and movies were made.  Whether you were paying attention or not you have seen these sets in countless films.  From the original Gotham City Hall to Mrs. Deagle's house in Gremlins. From Hazzard County to the ER hospital bay.  From Kermit's swamp to the theatre where Sheldon steals Raiders of The Lost Ark.  From...  The list goes on and on.  We sat on the couch from Friends and visited The Big Bang Theory & Pretty Little Liars sound stages.  Try to take as many pictures as you can as a little research will reveal that some movie or show you love came to life in that very spot.</Review>

< Name>
Bart Silvius<//Name>
< user_id>
103676518876931854672</user_id>
< Text>
Not really worth the price and $12 parking.

After waiting in a fine waiting area the intro video was a good start, but during the actual tour the overacting and failing-to-be-funny guide 'Danny' just ran his rushed, rehearsed spiel. Some tidbits where interesting but overshadowed by bad jokes and annoying voices. Repeatedly talking about how great the 'halloween tour' was really serves no purpose but to make me wonder if we had booked the wrong tour.

The content was almost exclusively about (long) past successes, like Friends, West Wing and ER. This made it hard to recognize some stuff. Maybe a tablet showing specific stills or videos of the scenes shot of things or places could have been nice to connect the place with the movie magic.

The carts were in a bad state, with loose trim, PA audio dropping and a seatbelt getting stuck, but conceptually ok for the purpose.

The visit to props room was interesting, but I feel more time roaming a bit would be nice, This part felt very rushed.

The static exhibitions are fun as long as you are interested in the specific movies/universes. Some pieces were very dusty, showing a lack of care.

The script-to-screen exhibition at the end of the tour had some good (interactive) pieces, and the sound mixing demo was decent - again plenty of really dusty exhibits.

The backlot and soundstages are quite cool to see in real life, but I would have loved more 'behind the scenes' information like building techniques or a tour through 'the back' - I understand there are people working there, maybe on secret stuff, but a small exhibition showing how a set or prop is manufactured could be really cool.

It seemed they did not want to 'break the fourth wall' but that (for me) was one of the main reasons to do the tour!

All in all, I had expected a more in-depth and higher-quality tour.< /Text>

<review>An AMAZING experience... where else can you get up close to some of the most incredible stage sets, lighting, props & costuming etc in the world!!

Visited WB Studios on Wed 23 October 2017 on a very HOT 33¬∞/92F day at 1.30pm in the afternoon with my family of 2 adults (45 & 47yrs) 3 teenagers (13, 16 & 18yrs) & 2 kids (8 & 10yrs) - 7 in total.

We went on the 1:30pm tour with a tour guide called Alex - he definitely knew his stuff. He was informative, patient, didnt rush & answered any questions we had (even the dumb ones!! lol)
Alex drove us around to different parts of WB backlots & exhibits explaing stuff like the set & buildg designs, history of the place etc. Got to see stuff like Wonder Women exhibit, DC Exhibit, Batman, Superman, Harry Potter & Pennywises IT costumes, Golden Globe/Oscars trophies, Big Bang Theory, The Fosters & Central Perk etc.

Managed to get parking across the road it was free when we went there on Monday but I don't think u can park there frm Tues to Sat 10am - 6pm as it cud be staff parking?? So beware. There is other parking around but you may need to drive around a bit.

Entrance is through the BIG statues of Daffy Duck & Bugs Bunny.

Security guards check yr bags etc b4 going in.
You'll then be directed into the WB reception area that books the tours (we used our GO CARD LA to get in which I highly recommend BTW) from there you will be directed into another small movie room that shows a short 5-10min video hosted by Ellen about WB Studios. After tht a tour guides is assigned.

Each tour cart holds around 15-18 people (so dependg on those bkd in will determine the tour group size) On our tour we only had a small group of 12 which suited me fine.  You'll see other tour groups being guided around also as u go.

Some areas wont allow you to take photos or film stuff but the tour guide will advise you beforehand.

Booking tours online is all good but if yr like me & missed my original booked time of 12.30pm...duh (I knw LA traffic is what I blame tht on lol) it was good to knw tht they could fit us in on the 1.30pm tour. Tours run every 15mins so let thm knw if yr guna be late. Merchandisg area is cool but pricey.

I recommend the tour,... it might not be everyones cuppa tea but my family & I enjoyed it!!

Hope that helps :)</review><name>Zinnia Leaso<//name>< userid>

The groups are smaller in Paramount, each of the visitors gets headphones to listen perfectly the guide (in WS there is only the speakers from the minicar and it is not the perfect sound to listen the explanatilns), the WV visit itself is very much focused on museum-type and for you to buy merchandising instead of going to see the stages and places where they record the movies / TV series, at least it was like this in our visit. Hi!

My name is Caio, I'm from Brazil, did my Studio Tour today and really would like to give my feedback.

The WB Studio Tour is one of the most amazing experience that i had in my "touristic life" and really would like to say thank you so much for having people in your staff like Jesse (dark short hair, green eyes and wearing a Gryffindor necklace for badge). I didn't had time enough to see Harry Potter's costumes because I spent too many time taking pictures of DC's movies and I as really sad about that, not only because Im a huge fan of HP movies but because I study movies' costumes and said that to her at the end of my studio tour.

Then she SAVED my day asking her manager if someone could take me back to see HP costumes   and it happened! Matt (another guy that deserve all the compliments of the world for being so patient with me waiting till I finish taking pictures of all HP stuff) came and took me there. I know it maybe could a simple thing for you in WB Studios but it really made my day (i got a little emotional for that. serious.)

So thank you so much for the incredible staff that you have and for making everything that is possible to have your guests satisfied!

YOU GUYS ARE AWESOME!!!

Brazilian hugs for all of you and sorry for the poor english. lol

<date>1385077151393</date><rating>2<//rating><Text>For $50 it's quite a ripoff. They just drive you around the backlot and the outside of stages, and the guide tells you about what was used for what show. <GmapID>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<Review>The WB-Studios are famous in the younger times for their production of "Harry Potter"-movie Series, and "Batman", "Superman", TV shows like "The Ghost Whisperer" but their history goes far away back: like 1962 "The Music Man" with Shirley JOnes,  "A Star is Born" (1954 with Judy Garland), A REBEL WITHOUT A CAUSE... (1954, with James Dean), and it was the studios of western tv shows like "Cheyenne", "Bronco" with stars like Ty Hardin, Clint Walker, and back to the 1930 and 20's.

You can book online / make reservation for a small tour or book a VIP Tour which has a tour lenght of 5 - 6 hours incl. lunch (and maybe you see a celebrity).  The VIP Tour might be bit pricy but you see a lot incl. archives, sound-stages (walk in that sound stage and try to feel the atmosphere or ghost of James Dean), see the studios most famous cars, see the costumes (from the 1950s/60s).

FAZIT: personally I liked it. The Tour-Guide are well informed and I can give 5 stars.< /Review><Resp>None<//Resp><userid>116540196018193369880< /userid>< Time>
1471780070204</Time>

1472028395747</Date>
<gmap_id>0x80c2bf09218463db:0x48fb7ec9a5d6c988</gmap_id>< review>
This is my first review; and I probably wouldn't have reviewed now either if it weren't for my love for F.R.I.E.N.D.S and for the disappointment in my tour guide -SHANT.
This place is definitely a must-see place for all F.R.I.E.N.D.S. fans! It's a very short 2 hours tour; and then they drop you at Stage 48.
Do wear walking shoes and no high heels or uncomfortable footwear; as there is some walking involved. Maybe more walking if you have a good tour guide (my tour guide was horrible and fat; he didn't wanna walk)
The highlight was to sit on the Central Perk couch; and we also had lunch at the Central Perk Cafe. Stage 48 was the best in all of the tour!!! The staff at Stage 48 was amazing and great merchandise too! :)
Do enjoy Stage 48! You can hang out there for as much time as you like and it's really fun! Very friendly staff and amazing stuff to buy! The Cafe has really yummy stuff too!
Apart from the couch at Stage 48 (which we go to at the end of the tour); During the tour we got to enter the Geller House and we also saw Phoebe's Dad's (Frank Buffay) house from outside. Few locations from the Pretty Little Liars and more shows but we were more into FRIENDS.
The Picture Vault was definitely another highlight but we didn't get enough time in there! The Harry Potter stuff was really good too, but since I've been to the WB Studio Tour in Leavesden; this one was of course very tiny in comparison.

Now, for the downside; our tour guide was quite a bit of a disappointment! His name is SHANT; and he really didn't seem as good as the others.
We showed great interest in FRIENDS and TBBT; but I did not get see ANYTHING related to The Big Bang Theory!!! That was really disappointing. The other thing about this guy was that he didn't want to leave the cart and show us places on foot ONLY CUZ IT WAS TOO HOT! And he was too lazy to get up and do his job! He told us "the reason we're not hopping off our cart like the other tour groups is because it's so hot outside!" He didn't even care to ask our opinion, if we wanted to check out some sets or locations :(
And when the Harry Potter Costume place and the Batmobile place came; he would say "enjoy the AC!" I GUESS THE HOT WEATHER WAS ALL HE WAS CONCERNED ABOUT! I know it was hot; but we aren't gonna be visiting every other day and we really wanted to see everything! After all we PAID for it!
When we passed the F.R.I.E.N.D.S. stage (with the plaque on it); and he wouldn't stop for a picture unless we had to ask him to; to which he reluctantly agreed. (Thank God!)
He only had certain points to speak, and didn't make much of an effort to make it interesting for us!
Apart from his usual lazy self; he seemed to be quite a racist too! We told him we're touring the USA since the past 1 month; and the only thing he seemed happy about was that we were returning home in the coming week! We told him NYC was our last stop after LA, and then we'd return; and he says "OH THEN THAT'S OKAY IF YOU'RE GOING BACK!" I told him that's bad; and he couldn't care less!
I really feel I would have enjoyed the tour if i didn't have such a horrible, lazy and a racist tour guide!
Dear Shant!
If you're reading this; we have no interest in staying in a country where RACISTS like yourself reside! If you weren't lazy enough to do your job properly, I probably would have enjoyed my tour! If you don't like this job, then please go find another and stop spoiling other people's trips!
If you don't know; we spent MILLIONS to be there and we do not appreciate your racism towards us! Either do your job properly or have some shame and quit! You suck big time Shant!
At least try to be a better human Shant!
I hope you get well soon!
Best Wishes from India

All in all; DO GO FOR THE STUDIO TOUR!!! The tour is good if your guide is good!
I visited only for the Central Perk Couch; and I really did enjoy Stage 48; happy to be away from lazy fat Shant and very pleased with the staff at the gift shop and the cafe!

I really hope no one else has such a bad experience as we did; ONLY the tour guide SHANT is to be blamed!</review>

<Date>1451411060096<//Date>< Review>
A good studio tour. I arrived early and the staff bumped me up to an earlier tour without me asking for it.  Seant was the guide and did his job great.

Why only three stars then? Well. Sadly. A couple of days before I spent four hours at the Universal theme-park. And wow. You just get so much more for your money there (basically at the same cost). Rides are included, their tour has elements of a ride in itself with explosions, flooding sets, actors animatronics and 3D simulation rides. And right outside you have the Universal City for no admission fee at all with shuttles down to north hollywood. Again. No extra cost.

The staff at Warners did absolutely everything they could with what they had. I fault them in no way for that. But if you're not a real die hard fan of WB tv-shows an you can only do one of them for time. I would rather recommend the Universal Park and City.</Review>

< text>
(Translated by Google) I took a tour alone to see the studio set of the American drama Friends. I booked online for a popular tour and headed from the hotel by combining the metro and bus. It may be easier to go with Uber.

The tour is entirely in English and will drive you around the location sets used in various movies and dramas. If you like Warner Bros. Studio's work, such as Batman, Harry Potter, Big bang theory, Eren, you'll be excited.

At the end, it will be disbanded at the place of Friends and the shooting set of Big bang theory, so you can freely enjoy shooting and buying souvenirs. There is a cameraman in each studio set, so even one person is fine. It will shoot with both the camera you purchased and the camera you bring. Make it feel like you can make a group and chat with people with a mug! I was a little envious because he gave me a pose theme.

It was a happy memory to sit on the Friends sofa, which has been an encouragement for studying English for many years, and to have a meal at Central Perk Cafe at the end.

(Original)

<Response>None<//Response><rate>5</rate><Text>(Translated by Google) A few years ago, I participated in this tour around the Hollywood movie.
The tour starts when it is time to make an online reservation. Take a bus in a group and go around the studio.
We will go around various places with explanations such as city sets, sound stages, TV sets used in movies and dramas.

The information about the recording room was very interesting because of the difficulties behind making a movie.

Also, because it is Warner, various shooting costumes and props of DC Comics are lined up. Anyway, I am impressed that the Real Batmobile is doing maintenance right there.

I never get tired of Harry Potter's CG photography or the composition studio.

Lastly, there is a shop limited to studios.
The stories and exhibits are more than big crops, but if you like movies, this tour is definitely a must-visit.

(Translated by Google) If you are in LA, I recommend this tour. It's the best if you like movies, and you can see the movies, drama props, and places you didn't like. You can make a reservation through the Internet in advance.
When you take your car, you can park it in a nearby underground parking lot. Don't just go to the start time, go leisurely, and have a coffee right next to the building where you get your ticket before the tour starts.
Tour guides go around explaining the places and episodes. Sometimes the stops are different for each tour guide, but it doesn't seem to make a big difference.
The Batman car is also bigger than you think, allowing you to freely spend time, watch and take photos there. In another prop room, you can see a variety of drama and movie props. There are restaurants and souvenirs available for you to drink food or coffee after the tour.

(Original)

<Rate>4</Rate><Review>(Translated by Google) For movie lovers a real must-see cult. Certainly the best tour of the studios in Los Angeles (paramount and Sony significantly lower, while Universal studios are more of a theme park). The staff is kind and seems to love what they do ... They are all guys who put enthusiasm in telling you about the studios' curiosities and anecdotes. The guides speak only Spanish or English so if you only know Italian you know that you will lose something in the visit. For lovers of la la land you will see the film cafeteria as well as next to one of the sheds the lampposts used on the set and then unfortunately removed from the locations that live do not appear as magical as in the film. Why don't I give 5 stars? For something trivial in itself but rather serious. The basic tour in fact does not cost little but incredibly the various groups of visitors do not see the same things! In fact, since there are many people, the organization decides from time to time which tour will make a single group ... My friends and I did the same tour after 15 minutes ... The result was that I saw beautiful things like the Manhattan rebuilt and a set of a sit com set in a high school while they saw something else and were not so enthusiastic ... I therefore recommend when you arrive to already know what you want to see and to claim from the staff to be put in the "right" group

<Review>(Translated by Google) It is very good to visit several places where several films and series were filmed.
The tour is sensational and you have the opportunity to see some special effects up close, scenarios, objects and costumes.
Visiting the old Friends studio and seeing a flood simulation up close was the highlight of the visit for me.
The guide spoke rather quickly to anyone who was dealing with tourists, but nothing that compromised the magic of the place.
The 4D experience is also very cool.

(Translated by Google) Our second studio tour in the past two years. Here you could see many filming locations on the studio grounds. For example, see Shameless, Pretty Little Liars, Friends, Ellen, Big Bang Theory, etc. Really exciting. You could even visit some sound days and a small museum. The second time was also worth it, although the first time was even better because of the Supergirl sound days.

(Translated by Google) We did the tour in Spanish with Bob. The best guide by far !! We had fun the whole tour. His Spanish was excellent and he is very cool. If you like series or movies, it is a must do !!.
We toured locations of Pretty Little Liars, Friends, Gilmore Girls, the Big Bang Theory, La La Land, Spider-man, La M√°scara, among others.
It lets you take photos wherever you want, and explains everything! Would go back !!

There is a part of the tour where you go to the part of furniture, objects and everything of props very interesting.
You can shoot a video on a harry potter broom or on the batman motorcycle with green screen.
It ends in Friends central perk where they take a photo of you.

I went in February 2017.

(Translated by Google) The WB Studio Tour is definitely worth it!
During a tour of around 2 hours, you will learn a lot about the creation of films and series. You drive in small groups of around 10 people across the area and are accompanied by a guide. You get off at various stations and explore the sets and buildings up close.

In addition, during the tour you visit an exhibition with various props and finally a kind of museum, where you can learn even more about the creation of films.

Our tour guide was very experienced and was able to give us a lot of exciting information about the individual parts of the studio and the films and series shot there.

(Original)

<Review>(Translated by Google) It is a true studio tour that has not been converted into a theme park like Universal Studios.
I went there a long time ago, but at that time I was really into the drama of ER, and I was really impressed by the fact that I could actually see a back door set with a basketball goal post.
They will also guide you through a trolley for friends and other sets.
I can not put it in the place where I am shooting, but it goes around the set actually used. In some cases, it seems to accept customer requests.
Also, the guide will answer not only the one-sided explanation but also the customer's question. At the end, I stopped by an exhibition room for movies and other small items (I used to be Harry Potter at the time) and then saw a little movie and ended.
It was quite fulfilling. Before I went, I thought it was a little expensive (it's actually expensive, this), but I had a good experience.
However, of course, it is all English, so if you can't hear English to some extent, it may be half the fun.

Access is quite difficult. When I went there, I rented a car, but there seems to be a bus stop, so I might be able to go by bus. However, if a person who is not a local wants to go by bus, he or she will get lost unless it is carefully examined in advance.
Furthermore, it's a fairly popular tour, so whether or not I can join it suddenly without making a phone reservation. I couldn't make a reservation because I didn't make a reservation because I was alone, so I managed to slip in, but other guests were refused.

Those who are troubled with everything are quite expensive, but it seems that there is an optional tour with transportation to the hotel. However, it seems that the tour will be attended only by guests, although there will be people who can speak Japanese.

(Translated by Google) The tour is a cheek for $ 300 per person. The food is rather modest. Everything in the studios is old and neglected. If you then take a picture or video in front of the green screen towards the end, you will be asked to checkout again. You can absolutely save the tour.
The Universal Studio VIP Tour, on the other hand, is awesome, invest your money here and you will also be treated like a VIP!
